Failing test: "should bring a dead cell to life that has exactly 3 live neighbors (reproduction)"
The test uses [[0, 0], [1, 0], [0, 1]] and expects the result to contain [1, 1].

Current implementation only handles survival. It needs to also find dead cells adjacent to living cells that have exactly 3 live neighbors.

Current code:
```typescript
export type Cell = [number, number];

function countNeighbors(cell: Cell, livingCells: Cell[]): number {
  return livingCells.filter(
    (other) =>
      !(other[0] === cell[0] && other[1] === cell[1]) &&
      Math.abs(other[0] - cell[0]) <= 1 &&
      Math.abs(other[1] - cell[1]) <= 1
  ).length;
}

export function nextGeneration(livingCells: Cell[]): Cell[] {
  return livingCells.filter((cell) => {
    const neighborCount = countNeighbors(cell, livingCells);
    return neighborCount === 2 || neighborCount === 3;
  });
}
```

To add reproduction:
1. Collect all dead neighbor cells of all living cells (candidates for reproduction)
2. For each candidate dead cell, count its live neighbors
3. If exactly 3, it becomes alive
4. Combine survivors with newly born cells

Make sure all 7 active tests pass. Run tests with: pnpm test

